## Reflection
One homework assignment that I found especially valuable was the problem set where we analyzed the heat transfer in a solar panel system using a thermal resistance network. I chose this assignment because it felt very applicable to real engineering situations. It required combining several heat transfer concepts—conduction, convection, and radiation—and understanding how they interact within the same system. Working through the problem helped me see how these mechanisms can be modeled together using a resistance network, which made the overall heat transfer process much clearer. It also gave me experience analyzing conduction through multiple material layers, which is common in many real devices.

After completing this assignment, I feel much more comfortable breaking down a physical system into a thermal model and analyzing heat transfer through layered materials. This is useful because many engineering systems require careful thermal management, especially electronics or energy systems where overheating can affect performance. Understanding how to model these situations will be important for future engineering work, whether it involves designing electronic components, energy devices like solar panels, or systems where temperature control is critical such as spacecraft or other advanced mechanical systems.